    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course! A \"confidentiality period\" is a set timeframe during which the parties involved in a contract must keep certain information private. It's like a temporary agreement to not share the sensitive details with outsiders. On the other hand, a \"survival clause\" in a contract is a provision that ensures certain terms or conditions continue to apply even after the contract has ended. Think of it as a safety net to protect your interests beyond the life of the contract. Both are important to understand, but they serve different purposes in a legal agreement.",
      "source": "target",
