    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I'm actually looking at a specific section right now regarding \"indemnification.\" It's a pretty long paragraph about being responsible for losses or damages if a breach occurs. Can you explain what that actually means for me in plain English? Like, what kind of stuff am I actually liable for?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! When a contract mentions indemnification, it's saying that one party agrees to cover any losses or damages that happen because of a breach of the agreement by the other party. In simpler terms, it's like saying, \"If I accidentally break your vase, I'm the one who's going to pay for the replacement.\" This could include things like lost money, legal fees, or any other costs related to the breach. It's a way to protect the other party and ensure that the responsible party steps up to cover the costs. Think of it as a safety net for the damages caused by the breach.",
      "source": "target",
